# What is this about?

Todays introduction into `git` features all you need for daily work.

This lecture covers the most basic `git` usages like:

* `clone` - copy a repository
* `blame` - show last change info
* `commit` - save changes
* `push` - upload changes
* `pull` - fetch and merge
* `rebase` - integrate changes linearly
* `reset` - undo changes
* `stash` - save changes temporarily
* `tag` - mark specific points
* `worktree` - multiple working directories
* `bisect` - find bugs via binary search
* `branch` - create/manage branches
* `rm` - remove files
* `mv` - move/rename files
* `svn` - interact with Subversion
* `revert` - undo commits
* `diff` - show differences
* `submodule` - use nested repositories

See <https://git-scm.com/docs> for detailed description.

Online resources: 

* <https://git-scm.com/learn>
* <https://learngitbranching.js.org/>

## Workflows

* **fork** & **PRs** (Pull Requests), 
* **issues** (markdown) and 
* **documentation** (README.md)

* Gitflow|GitHub|GitLab Flow <https://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/>

## Lecture 1: Looking into existing git repositorries

Call this command:

```sh
git clone https://github.com/nixcloud/git-training
```

* `git status` - Displays the state of the working directory and staging area.

  * What branch are you in? 
    
    [[!hiddentext You are in 'main', this is the default branch set in this repo. It could also be any other branch name... ]]

* `git branch` 

  * How to list remote branches?

    [[!hiddentext `git branch -r` will show remote branches, sometimes it requires a `git fetch --all` to update the local knowledge about the remotes. ]]

  * Change into branch **1_branch_with_many_commits**, what is the command to do so?

    [[!hiddentext `git checkout 1_branch_with_many_commits`]]

* `git log` - Shows the commit history. Options: `--oneline`!

  * What is the commit hash of the commit with the message: **adding new_file**?

    [[!hiddentext d22e0c8 adding new_file ]]

* `git blame README.md`

  * The README.md had many changes, identify the user who added the top most fox!

    [[!hiddentext a1389ad9 (Foxhunt         2026-03-18 14:27:44 +0000  8) ­¤”Ŗ U+1F98A Fox Face Unicode Character ]]

* `git diff` - Shows changes between commits. 

   * Figure out what happened between commit **1397c7** and **5c33c4**
   
     [[!hiddentext The chicken army got erased by the fox! `git diff 1397c7..5c33c4` is the command to see what happened! ]]



## Lecture 2: Initializes a new Git repository

There are a few ways to do this:

1. You create a repository with a README.md on the server, on the client you usually type:

    ```bash
    git clone https://github.com/nixcloud/git-training
    ```

    We already did this!

2. Local git repo first, then add remote:

    * create a new directory and `cd` into it
    * `git init` - Initializes a new Git repository
    * Next create an **new empty git repo** on your server
    * Finally add the remote (we skip this for now)

        ```
        git branch -M master
        git remote add origin git@github.com:qknight/test.git
        git push -u origin master
        ```

3. From SVN: `git svn clone <repository-url>` - Imports an SVN repository into a new directory.

    ```bash
    svn checkout https://svn.code.sf.net/p/svnexample/code/trunk svnexample
    ```

    Do this checkout now! How many commits does it have in git?

    [[!hiddentext the answer is: <pre>16</pre> ]]

## Lecture 3: `git commit`, `git uncommit`, `push`, `push -f` and `git reset`

`git add a_file` adds a file into the staging area. A following `git commit` converts it into **git object**, see [Git-Objects](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Internals-Git-Objects).

Now do this:

1. modify the README.md, add some section
2. call `git add README.md`
3. finally figure out how to undo this `git add` (sadly not `git unadd`)

[[!hiddentext `git reset README.md`, afterwards check that `git status` still shows changes and that your lines edited are still there ]]

### Command `git push -f`

Sometimes, after a commit & push you find out that you forgot something. You could add another commit but ... maybe it would be nice to not have a broken history. 

Typical scenario: 

* forgot fmt
* test execution fails

There are two options now:

* you can make the change and use `git commit --amend` and `git push -f` afterwards

  When is this a good idea and when to not do it? Research using google or AI!

  [[!hiddentext `git push -f` breaks history, if someone else already checked this out and work on top of it, his later push will fail - repaiable but bad. ]]

* you can undo your commit and return to the previous commit

  Find out how to do this, assume you made just one commit.

  [[!hiddentext `git reset --hard HEAD^` and then `git log` and if happy `git push -f` ]]

Finally figure out what the difference between `git reset HEAD --hard` vs. `git reset HEAD --soft`.

### Command `git pull`

A traditional 'git pull' uses the merge strategy, which works remarkably well but renders the commit history hard to read, makes rebasing a nightmere.

1. first clone `git clone https://github.com/sumantabose/git-playground`
2. cd git-playground
3. `tig`

  How many merge(s) do you see?

  [[!hiddentext With top commit 38922f it should be 6 M merge commits ]]

So a typical scenario: Two devs clone the same commit in `main` and start working. Dev A commits first with `git add files` and `git commit -m 'change'` and `git push`.

However, dev B needs to do something before pushing:

1. `git fetch --all`
2. `git rebase`
3. `git push`

An alternative to these 3 commands is:

```bash
git config --global pull.rebase true
```

And call `git pull` or even better, just always use:

```
git rebase origin/main
```

## Lecture 4: The `git branch` command

Switch to a different branch:

 `git checkout <branch-name>`

Sometimes we need to test something else but don't want to commit so:

1. `git status` shoould show it is an git branch with no modifications
2. Modify a file like README.md, add a few lines
3. `git stash`
4. `git status` again, what changed?

How to get the files back?

[[!hiddentext `git stash apply` on a clean git repo will reapply the changes. ]]

Finally we'll have a look what local branches have which remotes using:

`git remote -v`

Also have a look at `cat .git/config`, which is usually a good source for such things as well.

### `git tag`

A git tag is applied to a commit and not a branch, so do this:

1. add a tag 'v0.1.1' to the 'main' branch
2. since we forgot it figure out how to add a tag one a previous commit with 'v0.0.9'

How to upload the tags?

[[!hiddentext `git push --tags`. ]]

Note: If you ever set a tag, never, _NEVER_ change it, just add a new one with an increased version number.

## Lecture 5: The `git bisect` command

We have a branch with many commits but weeks later a fault was detected running `python main.py`. For some reason it stopped working but we don't know when nor why. **We need to find the commit which caused the issue!**

1. checkout the branch: `git checkout 2_bisect`
2. run the command: `python main.py` and see if it is working

We use `git bisect` for this. It is controlled with a few helper commands `start`, `good`, `bad` and `reset`.

Which commit introduced the issue? Verify the source code with `python main.py`, it must always show **Success**, then it is good. Otherwise it is bad!

 [[!hiddentext The issue started with commit 49f23ea3df2bd04a4ff323c63a2849907c0a30bb ]]

## Lecture 6: git history & rewrite

History in git can be rewritten for parts which have not been shared with others. That is: 

* You work on your branch 'branchiii' which is on top of 'main'
* You work on 'main' but everyone is on holidays or it is early in the morning
* You are forced to do the change (legal) and the others have to adapt....

### Changing a commit

Challenge: We have a branch with 5 commits on top of 'main'. We need to modify commit 3 which has a file added we don't want and the commit messsage needs to be changed as well. Afterwards we force push the commit

### Squashing commits

Squashing **multiple commits** manually into **one commit**. This is nice when you merge one branch into `main`. But when is commit smashing safe?

```bash
git rebase -i ...some-hash...
```

Then use:

```bash
# s, squash <commit> = use commit, but meld into previous commit
# f, fixup [-C | -c] 
```

Then select the commits


